 12  /-
 13  These synonyms for `list` are used to clarify the meanings of the many
 14  usages of lists in this module.
 15  
 16  - `listΣ` is used where a list represents a disjunction, such as the
 17    list of possible constructors of an inductive type.
 18  
 19  - `listΠ` is used where a list represents a conjunction, such as the
 20    list of arguments of an individual constructor.
 21  
 22  These are merely type synonyms, and so are not checked for consistency
 23  by the compiler.
 24  
 25  The `def`/`local notation` combination makes Lean retain these
 26  annotations in reported types.
 27  -/
 28  @[reducible] def list_Sigma := list
id                                  └──┘
src                                 └──┘
typ                                 └──┘
doc    └───────┘
 29  @[reducible] def list_Pi := list
id                               └──┘
src                              └──┘
typ                              └──┘
doc    └───────┘
 30  local notation `listΣ` := list_Sigma
id                             └────────┘
src                            └────────┘
typ                            └────────┘
 31  local notation `listΠ` := list_Pi

src                            └─────┘

125  /--
126  Takes the number of fields of a single constructor and patterns to
127  match its fields against (not necessarily the same number). The
128  returned lists each contain one element per field of the
129  constructor. The `name` is the name which will be used in the
130  top-level `cases` tactic, and the `rcases_patt` is the pattern which
131  the field will be matched against by subsequent `cases` tactics.
132  -/
133

135    nat → listΠ rcases_patt → listΠ name × listΠ rcases_patt

391  /--
392  The `rcases` tactic is the same as `cases`, but with more flexibility in the
393  `with` pattern syntax to allow for recursive case splitting. The pattern syntax
394  uses the following recursive grammar:
395  
396  ```
397  patt ::= (patt_list "|")* patt_list
398  patt_list ::= id | "_" | "⟨" (patt ",")* patt "⟩"
399  ```
400  
401  A pattern like `⟨a, b, c⟩ | ⟨d, e⟩` will do a split over the inductive datatype,
402  naming the first three parameters of the first constructor as `a,b,c` and the
403  first two of the second constructor `d,e`. If the list is not as long as the
404  number of arguments to the constructor or the number of constructors, the
405  remaining variables will be automatically named. If there are nested brackets
406  such as `⟨⟨a⟩, b | c⟩ | d` then these will cause more case splits as necessary.
407  If there are too many arguments, such as `⟨a, b, c⟩` for splitting on
408  `∃ x, ∃ y, p x`, then it will be treated as `⟨a, ⟨b, c⟩⟩`, splitting the last
409  parameter as necessary.
410  
411  `rcases` also has special support for quotient types: quotient induction into Prop works like
412  matching on the constructor `quot.mk`.
413  
414  `rcases h : e with PAT` will do the same as `rcases e with PAT` with the exception that an assumption
415  `h : e = PAT` will be added to the context.
416  
417  `rcases? e` will perform case splits on `e` in the same way as `rcases e`,
418  but rather than accepting a pattern, it does a maximal cases and prints the
419  pattern that would produce this case splitting. The default maximum depth is 5,
420  but this can be modified with `rcases? e : n`.
421  -/
422  meta def rcases : parse rcases_parse → tactic unit
id                     └───┘ └──────────┘ ┴ └────┘ └──┘
src                    └───┘ └──────────┘   └────┘ └──┘
typ                    └───┘ └──────────┘ ┴ └────┘ └──┘
doc                    └───┘ └──────────┘          └──┘

429  /--
430  The `rintro` tactic is a combination of the `intros` tactic with `rcases` to
431  allow for destructuring patterns while introducing variables. See `rcases` for
432  a description of supported patterns. For example, `rintro (a | ⟨b, c⟩) ⟨d, e⟩`
433  will introduce two variables, and then do case splits on both of them producing
434  two subgoals, one with variables `a d e` and the other with `b c d e`.
435  
436  `rintro?` will introduce and case split on variables in the same way as
437  `rintro`, but will also print the `rintro` invocation that would have the same
438  result. Like `rcases?`, `rintro? : n` allows for modifying the
439  depth of splitting; the default is 5.
440  -/

462  /--
463  The `obtain` tactic is a combination of `have` and `rcases`.
464  `obtain ⟨patt⟩ : type,
465   { ... }`
466  is equivalent to
467  `have h : type,
468   { ... },
469   rcases h with ⟨patt⟩`.
470   The syntax `obtain ⟨patt⟩ : type := proof` is also supported.
471   If `⟨patt⟩` is omitted, `rcases` will try to infer the pattern.
472   If `type` is omitted, `:= proof` is required.
473  -/
